many","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kurtz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for someone who was short in stature, from Middle High German <i>kur(t)z</i>, German <i>kurz</i> ‘short’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kurz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erna, Hans, Jutta, Armin, Benno, Fritz, Gunter, Heinz, Hermann, Horst, Manfred, Otto.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Kurtz  ."]},{"name":"Kurta","meanings":["Hungarian: nickname from German   Kurtz   ‘short’.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from Polish, Ukrainian, Belorussian <i>kurta</i> ‘short overcoat’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for someone who made such garments or possibly a nickname for someone who habitually wore a coat of this kind."]},{"name":"Kurtzman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman.","Americanized form of German <b>Kurtzmann</b>, and a variant of the same Jewish (Ashkenazic) surname: nickname for someone who was short in stature, a variant of   Kurtz  ."]},{"name":"Kurtzer","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname from an inflected form of   Kurtz   ‘short’."]}]},{"name":"Sebastian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Sebastianus</i>, the name of a 3rd-century saint, a Roman soldier martyred by the arrows of his fellow officers. His sufferings were a favourite subject for medieval artists. The name means ‘man from <i>Sebastē</i>’, a city in Asia Minor so called from Greek <i>sebastos</i> ‘august, venerable’, used as a translation of the Latin imperial title <i>Augustus</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sebastian Kurtz was born on 9 March 1614, in Überkingen, Oberamt Geislingen, Württemberg, Germany as the son of Peter Kurtz and Maria Vetter. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"9 March 1614–":"9. märts 1614–Surnud","1608–16